§⁰- This is only an illustration of the rule that the status of children born of lawful wedloclr was determined at the rime of their conception, because they followed the condition of their father: ‘hi qui legitime con· cipiuntur ex conceptionis tempore statum sumunt' Gaius i. 89. On the other hand, illegitimate children followed the condition of their mother, being ‘spurii’ Tit. ro. 12 supr, and accordingly in the time of Gaius their condition was determined by her status at the time of birth: for the later modification of this rule see Tit. 4, and note supr.

If the potestas were terminated in sorne mode by which the tilius· familias underwent capitis deminutio, he ceased to belong to his previous agnatic family, and thereby lost all his rights of intestate succession and guardianship to its members: consequently the distinction between modes in which this occurred and those in which ir did not is im· portant. The former are three in number: loss of libertas or civitas (apert frorn the ius postliminii), emancipation, and subjection to some other power, whether potestas, manus, or mancipium (e. g. the latter as produced in noxal surrender before Justinian).
